tspan.tspan: Pipette solutions are typically filled with a highly mobile cation (K or Cs) but
less mobile anion (gluconate or methanesulfonate). The less mobile ion does
not move as quickly and accumulates in the pipette, resulting in a liquid
junction potential (LJP). The LJP is eliminated when whole-cell configuration
is established, but if meter voltage was zeroed when the LJP was present,
the LJP will be added to all voltage readings.
